# **How to do Repairs**

This document is intended to provide an overview, and reference guide, for how boats go together and how we should be repairing boats, and other bits of kit. This covers the whole range of scales from ongoing care to catastrophic damage. Ideally this means that jobs can be delegated while maintaining a consistent approach and effective knowledge transfer.

# **Hardware** {#hardware}

We use a pretty large variety of hardware, most of which we can buy from a generic supplier,  [westfield fasteners](https://www.westfieldfasteners.co.uk/) is our go to at the moment. To buy rowing specific parts there are a number of useful websites; [Neaves](https://neaves-rowing.com/), [Swift](https://rowingcentre.co.uk/shop/overview), [Oarsport](https://oarsport.co.uk/), and [Eurow](https://www.eurow.eu/en/parts-rowing-boats.html).

| âœ”ï¸ | Hardware should be at least A2 Stainless |
| :---- | :---- |
|  | A4 is best for marine environments, but A2 can work |

Washers should always be used on bolts to help spread the load and protect the boats, and thus should be closest to the boat. We then also use a split washer to lock it against vibration. The only time a washer isn't needed is when there is an inbuilt one or a flanged bolt. When tightening bolts onto split washers donâ€™t crush the split washer or it loses the locking ability.

#  **Boats** {#boats}

## **Boat care & routine maintenance** {#boat-care-&-routine-maintenance}

To keep the boats in good condition there are a number of routine things we should be doing.

**Every outing**

- Wash the inside and out with soap and then fresh water and wipe dry with a microâ€‘fibre cloth  
  - Hull  
  - Riggers  
  - Runners

**Maintenance days**

- Remove hardware, clean and check missing washers etc.  
- Check for cracks in seats/riggers/footplates  
- Clean hull with Starbrite Hull Cleaner (WASH THIS OFF AFTER)  
- Remove limescale with diluted vinegar (WASH THIS OFF AFTER)

**Periodically**

- Machineâ€‘polish with fineâ€‘cut compound on a foam pad at low RPM

## **Composite Repairs** {#composite-repairs}

[Vacuum bagging (7th Ed.)](https://eu.westsystem.com/app/uploads/2022/10/VacuumBag-7th-Ed.pdf) / [Fiberglass in general](https://eu.westsystem.com/app/uploads/2022/10/Fibreglass-Manual-2015.pdf)  
We try to do minor repairs in house to avoid the high cost of sending them away. Many external places have minimum quotes of \~Â£450 and our insurance excess is Â£250. Although for the nicer boats it is still worth sending them.

### Construction {#construction}

The boats are generally built with a composite sandwich structure with carbon/kevlar skins of \~3 200g plys and a Nomex honeycomb core. When originally made this will be prepreg under vacuum in an autoclave. This is then covered with either 2K automotive style paint or gelcoat in some older/cheaper cases. 

These pose a problem for repairs as we canâ€™t use those paints due to safety concerns without a spray paint booth, and canâ€™t bake our boats at high temperature. However we can do a vacuum bagged wet layup and have carbon and core material, as well as decent quality aerosol paints.

# **Oars** {#oars}

Nearly all of our new blades are skinnies, with old ones generally being ultralight or Low I, although we have a whole range of blade shapes. Ideally we will standardise this over time as it allows for mixing and matching sets. The biggest factors in maintaining blades are cleaning the handles and having vortex tips to prevent scraping tips.

The main maintenance associated with blades are the handles needing replacing, including the end popping out, and the spoon itself deteriorating. Any larger damage would normally result in them being taken to C2 at  a major regatta for repairs, this should be organised in advance if possible.

## **Handles** {#handles}

Replacing handles is relatively easy for modern C2 ones, although we have a number of older ones that are directly epoxied on. The suede grips are also epoxied on and the suede itself should be removed, not the whole handle.

| âš ï¸ | There are two incompatible types of handle |
| :---- | :---- |
|  | Old ultralights use the [larger handle](https://www.concept2.co.uk/product/168), while new oars or skinnies/sculls need the [standard ones](https://www.concept2.co.uk/product/62). |

### [Suede replacement](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BxoXXjtqYGc) {#suede-replacement}

Suede squares need to be put on carefully so the seam doesn't cause blisters, and should be the right size for [sculls](https://www.concept2.co.uk/product/448) or sweep [inside](https://www.concept2.co.uk/product/174)/[outside](https://www.concept2.co.uk/product/173). They can be removed with a heat gun and patience, the surface should then be cleaned with IPA before a replacement is installed. The replacement patches have adhesive already installed.

### [Green rubber replacement](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wTvUfytJGFY) {#green-rubber-replacement}

Green grips must be unscrewed and fully replaced, if when this is done the end cap of the oar comes off too this must be epoxied back into place with Araldite taking care with the rotation.

### [Fixed handle replacement](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OvrIL5SpyT4) {#fixed-handle-replacement}

The fixed handle blades or the inner green grips can all be replaced in much the same way, as the suede and epoxied back into place. 

## **Sleeves** {#sleeves}

[The sleeves](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VKEmhbisczM&pp=0gcJCfwAo7VqN5tD) are just epoxied on too, however, they must be oriented correctly to set the pitch of the blade. There is a fancy C2 jig for this but you can do it with a flat reference surface. It boils down to the backside of the blade aligning with the P/S marking for port/starboard respectively. Make sure that the sleeve is positioned at the right distance from the spoon based on the gearing we need.

## **Steering wire** {#steering-wire}

We have a  number of different steering systems across the boats. They generally can all use the same wire though which is 2mm high grade [PVC coated stainless rope](https://www.wireropeshop.co.uk/clear-coated-pvc-stainless-steel-wire-rope-7x7/). Ideally we buy this direct for about 44p/m and don't pay a markup from a rowing shop at Â£3/m.

# **Seats** {#seats}

# **Coxbox Wiring** {#coxbox-wiring}

The wiring is relatively simple with a total of 5 pins on the main plug. These are split into the speakers, rate, and charging pins. Obviously not all are needed at all points so the wires swap down to 2 pin or 4 pin as and when needed.

## [**Troubleshooting**](http://www.redking.me.uk/sport/rowing/equipment/cox_box/nk_repairs.pdf) {#troubleshooting}

Refer to the document linked above for more comprehensive details on troubleshooting.

- A to D should connect to a magnet if present in the boat, shorting the connection periodically will show a stroke rate on the coxbox  
- C to B should be a short when the speakers are wired in  
- D to E (missing in diagram) should give 13.5-15V on the charger

The components of the harness are sold at a ridiculous markup by NKsports, Oarsport and activetools. This is obviously convenient but a 10x markup is obscene, thankfully it seems they are from the [Amphenol 44 series](https://www.amphenol-sine.com/pdf/catalog/44-Series.pdf).

## **Components** {#components}

### Coxbox Plug {#coxbox-plug}

[044 104 10004 02](https://www.mouser.co.uk/ProductDetail/Amphenol-SINE-Systems/044-104-10004-02?qs=tA%252Bq7m13GXUySe5HIfp6fg%3D%3D) This is a 4 pin receptacle, with the polarity of each pair not mattering.

### Speaker/Rate Plug {#speaker/rate-plug}

[044 103 10002](https://www.mouser.co.uk/ProductDetail/Amphenol-SINE-Systems/044-103-10002?qs=tA%252Bq7m13GXW6faQI3kLxYw%3D%3D), [044 104 10002 02](https://www.mouser.co.uk/ProductDetail/Amphenol-SINE-Systems/044-104-10002-02?qs=tA%252Bq7m13GXWv2d8caGUzFQ%3D%3D) These are 2 pin connectors with polarity not mattering. There seems to be some sort of convention on male/female for the main wire and speaker pick offs but who knows.

### Crimps {#crimps}

[044 100 1414P 100 101](https://www.mouser.co.uk/c/?q=044%20100%201414P%20100%20101), [044 102 1414S 100 101](https://www.mouser.co.uk/c/?q=044%20102%201414S%20100%20101) NK seems to be using some different gold crimps for their system. The solid ones are much nicer to work with but I havenâ€™t been able to locate them.

### Heat Shrink {#heat-shrink}

[DWFRÂ­6/2Â­0Â­STK](https://www.mouser.co.uk/ProductDetail/TE-Connectivity-Raychem/DWFR-6-2-0-STK?qs=YeFsEeYZIJnMEfWsJKC2lA%3D%3D), [DWFRÂ­16/4Â­0Â­STK](https://www.mouser.co.uk/ProductDetail/TE-Connectivity-Raychem/DWFR-16-4-0-STK?qs=YeFsEeYZIJkJLuipLRO0CA%3D%3D) We need to use heat shrink to protect the wires/plugs, and offer some sort of strain relief. These are epoxy filled so work well.

### Wires {#wires}

The 44 series is designed for anything between 14-18AWG. Potentially use [H07RNF](https://www.cef.co.uk/catalogue/products/2014148-1-5mm-2-core-ho7rnf-rubber-flexible-cable-cut-length-sold-by-the-mtr) or [YY control cable](https://www.cef.co.uk/catalogue/products/4835737-1-5mm-2-core-yy-control-flexible-cable-100m) 1.5mm2. The YY is cheaper but less well insulated/waterproof so may degrade a bit fast.
